-- Indonesia Stocks: AKR Corporindo, Bumi Resources, Indocement
-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 2012-01-05T09:18:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-05/indonesia-stocks-akr-corporindo-bumi-resources-indocement.html
Shares of the following companies had
 unusual (JCI)  moves in  Indonesian trading. (JCI)  Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the close in Jakarta.  The Jakarta Composite index lost 1.16 point, or less than
0.1 percent, to 3,906.26, the first drop in three days.       PT AKR Corporindo (AKRA)  (AKRA IJ), a fuel and chemical
distributor, gained 3.9 percent to 3,300 rupiah, closing at a
record. The company plans to invest $100 million to build tank
terminals, jetties and self-propelled oil barges and vessels for
its petroleum distribution business, Director Vembu Suresh said
by e-mail yesterday.       PT Bumi Resources (BUMI)  (BUMI IJ),  Indonesia ’s biggest coal
producer, rose 1.1 percent to 2,350 rupiah, the highest close
since Nov. 9.  PT Borneo Lumbung Energi & Metal (BORN)   is
considering buying a stake in Bumi’s mining unit  PT Bumi
Resources Minerals (BRMS)   at the end of 2012 or in 2013,
Investor Daily Indonesia reported, citing a person it didn’t
identify. Borneo Lumbung Corporate Secretary Geroad Panji Alamsyah Jusuf couldn’t be reached when called at his office.
Borneo Lumbung slid 1.2 percent to 830 rupiah and Bumi Minerals
fell 1.7 percent to 580 rupiah.  PT Indocement Tunggal Prakarsa (INTP)  , Indonesia’s
second-largest cement producer, advanced 1.9 percent to 18,400
rupiah, its highest close since Oct. 8, 2010. The company may
spend as much as $250 million this year as part of a $500
million investment to build two cement plants with annual
capacities of 2 million tons to 2.5 million tons, Kontan
reported, citing Corporate Secretary Sahat Pangabean. Three
calls to the company’s office in Jakarta weren’t answered.       PT Timah (TINS)  (TINS IJ), Indonesia’s largest tin producer, fell
1.2 percent to 1,680 rupiah, the first decline in seven days.
The government is studying the possibility of imposing a tax on
tin exports as a way to limit shipments and boost prices, Deputy
Trade Minister Bayu Krisnamurthi told reporters today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
